statement.p:
For each of the following matrices, find the eigenvalues and a
basis for each eigenspace.  Determine whether the matrix is
diagonalizable and, if so, find a diagonalization.  Determine
whether the matrix is orthogonally diagonalizable and, if so,
find an orthogonal diagonalization.











      \begin{bmatrix}
      5 \amp 1 \\
      -1 \amp 3 \\
      \end{bmatrix}








	\begin{bmatrix}
	0 \amp 1  \\
	1 \amp 0 \\
	\end{bmatrix}








	\begin{bmatrix}
	1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
	2 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\
	\end{bmatrix}








	\begin{bmatrix}
	2 \amp 5 \amp -4\\
	5 \amp -7 \amp 5 \\
	-4 \amp 5 \amp 2 \\
	\end{bmatrix}

li.p:
      This matrix is symmetric so it is orthogonally diagonalizable:

	D = \begin{bmatrix}
	1 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp -1 \\
	\end{bmatrix},\hspace{24pt}
	Q = \begin{bmatrix}
	1/\sqrt{2} \amp 1/\sqrt{2} \\
	1/\sqrt{2} \amp -1/\sqrt{2} \\
	\end{bmatrix}\text{.}

      This matrix is diagonalizable but not orthogonally
      diagonalizable.

	D = \begin{bmatrix}
	4 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
	\end{bmatrix},\hspace{24pt}
	P = \begin{bmatrix}
	0 \amp 9 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 6 \amp 6 \\
	1 \amp -2 \amp -1
	\end{bmatrix}\text{.}

      This matrix is symmetric so it's orthogonally
      diagonalizable.

	D = \begin{bmatrix}
	6 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 0 \amp -12 \\
	\end{bmatrix},\hspace{24pt}
	Q = \begin{bmatrix}
	1/\sqrt{2} \amp 1/\sqrt{3} \amp 1/\sqrt{6} \\
	0 \amp 1/\sqrt{3} \amp -2/\sqrt{6} \\
	-1/\sqrt{2} \amp 1/\sqrt{3} \amp 1/\sqrt{6} \\
	\end{bmatrix}\text{.}

      Diagonalizable, but not orthogonally
      diagonalizable.

	D = \begin{bmatrix}
	4 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
	\end{bmatrix},\hspace{24pt}
	P = \begin{bmatrix}
	0 \amp 9 \amp 0 \\
	0 \amp 6 \amp 6 \\
	1 \amp -2 \amp -1
	\end{bmatrix}\text{.}
